poses to the U.S. racial and security state. Beauchamp uses instances of gender surveillance to demonstrate how disciplinary power attempts to produce conformist citizens and regulate difference through discourses of security. At the same time, he contends that greater visibility and recognition for gender nonconformity, while sometimes beneficial, might actually enable the surveillance state to more effectively track, measure, and control trans bodies and identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aElectronic surveillancexPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aElectronic surveillancexSex differenceszUnited States. 0aElectronic surveillancexSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aGender identityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aGender nonconformityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aTransphobiazUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002659zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002659.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles